column1: # Kirrkirr pictures import file version 3 (2018). Pictures list last updated: 2018-08-31
# The file is in CSV format (fields containing commas should be quoted with double quotes).
# Each line is one picture; it can link to any number of words (even zero), as jaja, jajina*2*, etc.
# A word should exactly match a dictionary headword. The word can be followed by *num* to indicate a homonym number for homonyms.
# Except that lines beginning with the hash character (#), or double-quote followed by # if quoted, are assumed to be comments for humans.
# The character encoding of the file is assumed to be UTF-8.
# The “credits” (copyright, photographer) field will be placed in the XML dictionary file and overlaid on the photo; it should be valid XML.
# We will escape & and < for the XML, but the result will be placed as the value of an XML attribute and must be valid XML, so don’t go too wild with the contents.
# It should be reasonably short, so we can display it. Other source information may appear in the “otherNotes” field.
# Image processing uses rows A, B, E, and F.
# Valid values for imageProcessing are a comma-separated list of zero or more of: trim, autotone, crop(left;top;right;bottom)
# “crop” takes 4 semicolon-separated (NB!) arguments, each of which is pixels relative to the original picture size. So you pass something like “crop(30;10;0;0)” for  left and top cropping.
# Image processing can be given the value “none” to show that the image has been examined and no processing is necessary, but it is not required; a blank field has the same meaning.
# Kirrkirr dictionary preparation takes information from only columns A, E, and K (10) onwards
# Format (comma-separated values (CSV) columns, with double quotes around cells with commas):

Michand home page (http://www.faroc.com.au/~mhand/contents.html) Granites gold mine little spotted snake - what? A very pretty little snake of golden or pale brown colour. It feeds mainly at night with frogs, geckos, skinks and insects prominent on its diet.

Michand home page (http://www.faroc.com.au/~mhand/contents.html) Granites gold mine. Made distinctive by a patch of bright red on its neck. If threatened it puts on an aggressive display of rearing and striking at any moving object, but fortunately neglects to open its mouth. It obviously wants to save its venom for the more delectable prey of insects and small lizards which it seeks of a night. It is often found in association with termite colonies.
